From: gthaker@atl.ge.com (Gautam H. Thaker)
Subject: Windows NT,OS/2 and vRTX Real Time Perf. How would Linux do?
Date: 28 Sep 1993 16:29:13 GMT

In article <CE1tLp.qA@rice.edu> dboyes@is.rice.edu (David E Boyes) writes:

   Newsgroups: comp.realtime
   Path: newshost.atl.ge.com!sunblossom!news.crd.ge.com!sarah!newserve!ub!news.kei.com!sol.ctr.columbia.edu!usc!cs.utexas.edu!newsfeed.rice.edu!rice!dboyes
   From: dboyes@is.rice.edu (David E Boyes)
   Sender: news@rice.edu (News)
   Organization: Rice University
   References: <espritCE0pLK.2A5@netcom.com>
   Date: Tue, 28 Sep 1993 05:22:36 GMT
   Lines: 90

   In article <espritCE0pLK.2A5@netcom.com> esprit@netcom.com (Alan F. Perry) writes:
   >In contrast to the "is not/is so" slugfest going on over Windows NT, has
   >anyone tried any real-time benchmarks or, even better, tried porting their
   >application(s) on/to it.

   Well, to some extent, yes. I was tinkering with both OS/2 and NT
   to try to determine some of the RT characteristics of both to see
   if they would be suitable for a wave-soldering control system
   that I've been puttering with. A previous iteration of the
   control system ran under vRTX, so I used that as a reference
   implementation. 

   Hardware base was a 25Mhz 386/387 ISA bus clone w 16M real memory
   and 100M SCSI2 disk on an Adaptec SCSI controller and a General
   Instruments GPIB controller to the instrumentation bus, and a
   486/50 with 32M real memory and the same SCSI disk and GPIB
   board. Process times on the applicator station need timer control
   intervals of 50 usec +/- 4 usec for reliable reaction to overtemp
   or bad flow conditions. Below are some very rough results based
   on my home-grown execution profiler:

   Definitions (so everyone agrees on what's being measured): 

   sample size is 100 executions

   OS == the obvious
   timer skew == deviation from scheduled interval time using OS
                 timer facilities (no custom assembler or external
                 heartbeat timer used) Permissible deviation in this
                 case is +/- 4 usec to avoid component damage.
   avg interrupt latency == delay time from trigger condition to
                 first instruction of interrupt handler for device.
   avg interrupt service = total execution of interrupt service
                 (trigger to ready to accept trigger. interrupt
                 service routine executes only code to push measured
                 value into input process buffer and posts data
                 available to another process via an OS semaphore)

   Both OS/2 and NT measurements are with GUI running (to keep it
   fair) and with the process fixed in memory if possible (at
   minimum, marked non-swappable). The actual instrumentation setup
   is the same for both OSes. 


   OS   timer skew   avg interrupt latency   avg interrupt service
          (usec)          (usec)                 (usec)
   ----------------------------------------------------------------
   vRTX    +1              3.364                    24 
   OS/2    +2.25-+3.2      5.52                     31
   NT      -2.17-+4.77     5.14                     39

   Timer facilities in NT are of widely varying accuracy, although
   the OS/2 timer functions appear to vary in accuracy depending on
   the underlying hardware. The NT timer exceeded the deadline more
   than once, which made an awful mess of my bench space (8-(). It
   is a curious artifact that the interrupt latency time appeared to
   be somewhat shorter with NT, which I attribute to a better device
   driver for the GPIB card (the OS/2 driver still has a few
   gremlins). The vRTX implementation was rock solid and right on
   the money in every test (nice work, folks!) -- no detectable skew
   on the measured values in all 100 tests.

   Development facilities were a lot better on OS/2 than NT, but
   that's probably a function of OS/2 being out longer. Some kind
   soul (whose name escapes me at the moment) has tipped me off to a
   CD of the GNU tools for NT, which I'd expect to improve the
   tools on NT considerably. It was considerably more difficult to
   get the NT process locked in memory, mostly due to poor
   documentation, I think, but it took a lot more experimentation.
   The IBM last stage optimizer in the C compiler also is overall a
   bit better than the MS one -- it's proportionally slower, but
   makes very nice code. I'm also somewhat concerned with the
   limitations in NT with what system facilities can be called from
   a storage-fixed process -- some important stuff is somewhat
   difficult to call from a memory-mapped process, like semaphore
   manipulation. 

   I'm working on some more interesting results with a real
   application, which might be worth writing up if people are really
   interested. Based on what I've observed so far, I don't see NT or
   OS/2 displacing the vRTX and QNX user base for critical hard RT
   systems -- soft RT, maybe, but it'll take quite a bit of work.

   >Alan F. Perry               | Life is short, but by achieving greater speeds
   >esprit@netcom.com   (home)  | a man can make his life a little longer and
   -- 
   David Boyes      | This signature modified to be inoffensive to any race,
   dboyes@rice.edu  | color, creed, sexual orientation, or programming limitation.
   My opinion is my | Sober pursuit of truth and to all high ideals consecrated?
   own.             | Look, it says so right on the box, next to the Vitamin A.


It is possible to speculate on what the ave. interrupt latency and
avg. interrupt task switch latencies might be for Linux? 

What would it take to use Linux in real-time applications?


