From: urlichs@smurf.sub.org (Matthias Urlichs)
Subject: Re: Q: Serial port Control; need TD signal on so CallerID box will work
Date: 28 Sep 1993 12:15:47 +0100

In comp.os.linux.misc, article <27fsibINNq3s@apache.dtcc.edu>,
  joe@apache.dtcc.edu (Joe Brown) writes:
> 
> This is a caller ID device, grabbs power from three lines of serial
> port.
> 
>   TD (Transmit Data)          - the tricky one
Ugh.

>   CTS (Clear to Send)         - both of these are on, when simply
>   DTR (Data Terminal Ready)     by reading the serial line.
>                                 ie.  cat /dev/ttyS0
> 
> I can't figure out how to turn on the Transmit Data (TD) line, and 
> still read characters.  It looks like ioctl isn't implemented in
> the kernel, which I assume, the calls to perform this action, would
> exist.
> 
Do you actaully have to send anything? If not, why not simply connect TD to 
CTS on the caller-ID side?

If yes, you'll have to hack the kernel. Posix(?) says there are supposed to 
be TIOCSBRK / TIOCCBRK ioctl calls which set / clear the BREAK signal, which 
is just another name for a continuously-on TD wire.
You should be careful not to send anything else during that time, of course. 
;-)

